Case Study: Bike-Share

Project Description

The objective of this project is to perform real-world tasks of a data analyst for a fictional company Cyclistic. In order to answer the key business questions, we will follow the steps of the data analysis process: ask, prepare, process, analyze, share, and act.

Scenario

You are a data analyst working in the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the companys future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, your team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights, your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.

Ask

Guiding questions

  • What is the problem you are trying to solve? The primary goal is to devise a strategy that would persuade casual bike riders to upgrade to annual members.
  • How can your insights drive business decisions? The insights will help the market analyst team better understand how annual members and casual riders differ.

Key Tasks

1. Identify the business task

How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

2. Consider Key Stakeholders

Characters and teams

  • Cyclistic: A bike-share program that features more than 5,800 bicycles and 600 docking stations. Cyclistic sets itself apart by also offering reclining bikes, hand tricycles, and cargo bikes, making bike-share more inclusive to people with disabilities and riders who cant use a standard two-wheeled bike. The majority of riders opt for traditional bikes; about 8% of riders use the assistive options. Cyclistic users are more likely to ride for leisure, but about 30% use them to commute to work each day. s
  • Lily Moreno: The director of marketing and your manager. Moreno is responsible for the development of campaigns and initiatives to promote the bike-share program. These may include email, social media, and other channels.
  • Cyclistic marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts who are responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Cyclistic marketing strategy. You joined this team six months ago and have been busy learning about Cyclistics mission and business goals as well as how you, as a junior data analyst, can help Cyclistic achieve them.
  • Cyclistic executive team: The notoriously detail-oriented executive team will decide whether to approve the recommended marketing program.

Deliverable

Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members.
Find the key differences between casual rides and members, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics

Prepare

Guiding questions

  • Where is your data located?
    This project uses the Cyclistics historical trip data to analyze and identify trends.
    Data is extracted from this kaggle dataset
  • How is the data organized?
    The data is organized by month across 10 csv files.
  • Are there issues with bias or credibility in this data? Does your data ROCCC?
    There are no issues with bias or credibility in this data. The data is ROCCC: reliable, original, comprehensive, current and cited.
  • How are you addressing licensing, privacy, security, and accessibility?
    The data is provided by Motivate International Inc with the following licence
    The data is secure and accesibile: riders personally identifiable information isnt included in the data.
  • How did you verify the datas integrity?
    There are 10 csv files. In each file there are 13 consistent attributes.
  • How does it help you answer your question?
    The data provides some key insights about both the causal riders and the members.

Key tasks

  1. Download data and store it appropriately.
    All the files were downloaded
  2. Identify how its organized.
    The data is organized by month across 10 csv files.
  3. Sort and filter the data.
    I will be using R to sort and filter the data
  4. Determine the credibility of the data.
    The data is provided by Motivate International Inc with the following licence and is credible

Process

Key tasks

  1. Check the data for errors.
  2. Choose your tools.
  3. Transform the data so you can work with it effectively.
  4. Document the cleaning process.
  • Used Google Sheets to load all the csv files to view and clean data.
  • Added a column called ride_length. to calculate the length of each ride by subtracting the column started_at from the column ended_at and format it as duration(HH:MM:SS 373055).
  • Added a column called day_of_week, to calculate the day of the week that each ride started using the WEEKDAY command and format it in characters(1 =Sunday and 7 = Saturday).
  • Removed duplicates, and irrelevant data (example: rides that last more than a day)

Optional: explore the dataset, youll find these columns: ride_id, rideable_type, started_at, ended_at, start_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_id, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng, and member_casual.

  • The average ride duration of members is 15.7 minutes and that of casual rider is 47.4 minutes which is approximately 3 times higher compared to that of members.

  • For members the average ride time is consistent on weekdays for an average of 14.8 minutes and sees a slight increase to 18.1 minutes on the weekend.

  • For casual riders the week starts off to an average of 42 minutes from Monday till Wednesday and a slight increase to 46 minutes towards the end of the week(Thursday/Friday) and a jump to 54 minutes on the weekend.

Recommendations for increasing the number of rider membership are:

The highest demands for bikes is seen in the summer months from July to September for both casual riders and members. Almost 60% of the casual rides are during this time, which could be due to tourists and other events.

During these months we could:

  • Increase the availability of bikes.
  • Weekly, monthly subscription offers.
